<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/8f57f89db0c22071ea083ff3e12f4339> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Northern Plains feather headdress; hide, cotton, feathers, horsehair; h. 47 cm., d. 34 cm.; ca. 1860-1870s. \r\nPlains feather headdresses came in several types (cf. RMV 710-5), and this specimen is of the straight-up variety. In most cases they were associated with war honors, each black-tipped tail feather of the eagle representing a demonstration of exceptional bravery during an encounter with an enemy, and formally recognized by fellow warriors. Besides badges of honor, the eagle feathers were also often regarded as sources of supernatural power, required in raiding and warfare. The blood-red wrapping of the feathers' stems reinforces the association with warfare. Among the Blackfeet only a few leaders were allowed to wear an upright feather bonnet (Wissler 1910:124; Ewers 1958:118; cf. Woodruff 1934:634-5; Brasser 1976:84; Coe 1976:160,175; Thompson 1977:159,175; Conn 1979:165; 1982:105,146-7; Walton et.al. 1985:103-109; Hassrick and Markoe 1986:82;95; Penney 1992:215-220; Brokenleg and Hoover 1993:42,44,46,61-2; Flood 1996:62;  Brasser 2000:135,151).\r\n\r\nYanktonai men caught golden and bald mature eagles from pits, dug into the high bluffs overlooking the Missouri River. The holes were covered with a screen woven from willow branches, on which a stuffed rabbitskin and some red meat were fastened. The Indian trappers attracted the birds by poking the skin and meat with a stick, and caught the legs of the eagle when it swooped down to catch the prey. Buckskin gloves protected their hands. It was generally a communal affair of a group of men, who prepared themselves ritually for the catch, and followed prescribed rules for protecting themselves against the eagle's power (Howard 1954; cf. Wilson 1928).\r\n(Hovens 2008-09)\r\n\r\nDit type hoofdtooi, met rechtopstaande adelaarsveren, is een van de oudste typen. Aan de adelaar werd bovennatuurlijke kracht toegeschreven en krijgers probeerden die te verwerven door gebeden tot de mythische vogel te richten. Iedere veer moest verdiend worden door een moedige daad tijdens een krijgstocht en dergelijke hoofdtooien gaven de status van krijgers en leiders aan." .
